Bike Sharing Demand - Kaggle

Krishna Sandeep Dharga

June 25, 2019

Introduction

This project is to explore the Bike Sharing Demand dataset posted on Kaggle. The dataset can be found at https://www.kaggle.com/c/bike-sharing-demand/data

In this competition, participants are asked to combine historical usage patterns of bike sharing platforms with weather data in order to forecast bike rental demand in the Capital Bikeshare program in Washington, D.C.

Data and Problem Description (As posted on Kaggle)

You are provided hourly rental data spanning two years. For this competition, the training set is comprised of the first 19 days of each month, while the test set is the 20th to the end of the month. You must predict the total count of bikes rented during each hour covered by the test set, using only information available prior to the rental period.

Data Fields

  • datetime - hourly date + timestamp
  • season -
    • 1 = spring
    • 2 = summer
    • 3 = fall
    • 4 = winter
  • holiday - whether the day is considered a holiday
  • workingday - whether the day is neither a weekend nor holiday
  • weather -
    • 1 = Clear, Few clouds, Partly cloudy, Partly cloudy
    • 2 = Mist + Cloudy, Mist + Broken clouds, Mist + Few clouds, Mist
    • 3 = Light Snow, Light Rain + Thunderstorm + Scattered clouds, Light Rain + Scattered clouds
    • 4 = Heavy Rain + Ice Pallets + Thunderstorm + Mist, Snow + Fog
  • temp - temperature in Celsius
  • atemp - “feels like” temperature in Celsius
  • humidity - relative humidity
  • windspeed - wind speed
  • casual - number of non-registered user rentals initiated
  • registered - number of registered user rentals initiated
  • count - number of total rentals

We can see that attributes such as season, holiday, workingday & weather, have been identified as numeric. But it makes more sense for those attributes to be factors. So, let’s update data types of these attributes.

raw.data <- raw.data %>% 
              mutate(season = factor(season)) %>%
              mutate(holiday = factor(holiday)) %>%
              mutate(workingday = factor(workingday)) %>%
              mutate(weather = factor(weather))

Now that we have all data types identified correctly we can start to explore the data by using exploratory plots.

Let’s create plots based on questions that we can ask the data. We will formulate questions that the given attributes could potentially answer and try to answer them using visualizations.

Question 1 - Do we have equal number of observations for each level in the factor variables?

draw.plot1 <- function(data,x,a){
  plt <- data %>% ggplot(aes(x=x)) +
                    geom_bar(fill="blue",alpha=0.6) +
                    labs(x=a) +
                    theme_economist_white()
  return(plt)
}

p1 <- draw.plot1(raw.data,raw.data$season,'season')
p2 <- draw.plot1(raw.data,raw.data$holiday,'holiday')
p3 <- draw.plot1(raw.data,raw.data$workingday,'workingday')
p4 <- draw.plot1(raw.data,raw.data$weather,'weather')

grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,p4,nrow=2,ncol=2,top="Num of observations for each factor level")

From the above graphs we can see that:

  • season - we have almost equal number of observations for all 4 seasons.
  • holiday - we have more number of non-holidays than holidays, which makes sense.
  • workingday - we have more number of working days than non-working days, which makes sense.
  • weather - we have the most number of observations for weather type-1 (see above for definition) and none for weather type-4. This could be because weather type-4 is unlikely to occur in this region. In a real-world scenario, it is advisable to consult subject matter experts, or data owners to confirm if this is normal or an anamoly.

Question 2 - How are values of numeric attributes distributed in this dataset?

draw.plot2 <- function(data,x,a){
  plt <- data %>% ggplot(aes(x=x)) +
            geom_histogram(bins = 40, fill = "blue", alpha = 0.5) +
            labs(x=a) +
            theme_economist_white()
  return(plt)
}

p1 <- draw.plot2(raw.data,raw.data$temp,"temp")
p2 <- draw.plot2(raw.data,raw.data$atemp,"atemp")
p3 <- draw.plot2(raw.data,raw.data$humidity,"humidity")
p4 <- draw.plot2(raw.data,raw.data$windspeed,"windspeed")

grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,p4,nrow=2,ncol=2,top="Distribution of values of numeric attributes")

From the above graphs we can see that:

  • temp & atemp - the temperature in this region seems to be mostly in the range of 10deg to 35deg celcius.
  • humidity - humidity is almost normally distributed except for some peaks at around 80.
  • windspeeds - windspeeds also seems to be normal mostly except for a few very windy days.

Overall the dataset seems to suggest pretty normal weather conditions in this region. So it looks like we need not account for any severe weather conditions to predict demand for Bikes at this point of time.

Question 3 - What is the distribution of outcome variable ih the dataset?

The outcome variable is the count of Bikes hired in a day. There are three variables that describe that contain the count of bikes hired, i.e. casual, registered & count, where count=casual+registered. Let’s look at their distribution overall.

p1 <- draw.plot2(raw.data,raw.data$casual,'casual')
p2 <- draw.plot2(raw.data,raw.data$registered,'registered')
p3 <- draw.plot2(raw.data,raw.data$count,'total count')

grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,nrow=2,top="Distribution of outcome variables")

At first glance this distribution may look a little suspicious, because we see that casual & registered have high ‘0’ counts but total count does not have as many. But this could be because in cases where casual was 0, registered had some non-zero number, making total count also non-zero and vice-versa.

Let’s just verify that all observations follow the formula count=casual+registered just to be sure about the data.

count.verify <- sum((raw.data$casual + raw.data$registered) - raw.data$count)
print(count.verify)
## [1] 0

The count variables in all observations are good to go.

Let’s now look at how the outcome variable is distributed with respect to other variables.

Question 4 - How are Bike hire counts distributed in each month?

draw.plot3 <- function(data,y,a,y.max){
  plt <- data %>% mutate(month = as.factor(month(datetime))) %>%
                    ggplot(aes(month,y)) +
                      geom_jitter(alpha=0.5,color="red") +
                      geom_boxplot(color="blue",outlier.color=NA,alpha=0.5) +
                      scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0,y.max,by=50)) +
                      labs(y=a) +
                      theme_economist_white()
  return(plt)
}

p1 <- draw.plot3(raw.data,raw.data$casual,'casual',500)
p2 <- draw.plot3(raw.data,raw.data$registered,'registered',1000)

grid.arrange(p1,p2,nrow=1,top="Casual and Registered bike hires in each month")

From the above graphs we can notice two things:

  1. The median number of registered users hiring a bike is clearly higher than casual users in almost all months. So, it could be a good strategy for the company to get users to signup than to depend on casual users.

  2. Months 1, 2, 3, & 4 seem to have lower sales. This could be it is tougher to ride a bike in winter. Let’s further investigate this from the point of view of seasons.

First let’s see which month corresponds to which season.

Question 5 - How are Bike hire counts distributed in each season?

draw.plot4 <- function(data,x,y,a,b,y.max){
  plt <- data %>% ggplot(aes(x=x,y=y)) +
                    geom_jitter(color="red",alpha=0.5) +
                    geom_boxplot(color="blue",alpha=0.5, outlier.color = NA) +
                    labs(x=a,y=b) +
                    scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0,y.max,by=50))
                    theme_economist_white()
  return(plt)
}

p1 <- draw.plot4(raw.data,raw.data$season,raw.data$casual,'season','casual',500)
p2 <- draw.plot4(raw.data,raw.data$season,raw.data$registered,'season','registered',1000)

grid.arrange(p1,p2,nrow=1, top="Casual and Registered bike hires in each season")

These graphs are consistent with the ‘months’ graphs that we saw earlier. We can notice the following things from this graph:

  1. The number of bike hires by casual users drops in Winter and Spring (season 1 & 4 respectively).

  2. But it drops only in Spring for registered users. It is surprising to see that the number of hires by registered users remains consistent even in winter. This reinforces the idea of signing up more users to the service to maintain steady flow of revenues for most part of the year.

Question 6 - How does daily weather affect the number of bike hires?

p1 <- draw.plot4(raw.data,raw.data$weather,raw.data$casual,'weather','casual',500)
p2 <- draw.plot4(raw.data,raw.data$weather,raw.data$registered,'weather','registered',1000)

grid.arrange(p1,p2,nrow=1,top="Casual and Registered bike hire count by weather conditions")

From the above graphs we can see that both types of users hire fewer bike in Light Snow + Light Shower conditions, and the number of hires is negligible when there is Heavy Snow or Heavy Rain conditions, which makes sense. However, there seems to be one day in which 150+ bikes were hired registered users despite severe weather conditions. It would be good to investigate if this is an anamoly or if there was some issue with data collection.
